    "author_association": "MEMBER",
    "body": "Part of the ncurses changes that went along with [wide integer support](42f3cdd284735bd827691c3d0bfae9472b22d5d5) was supporting files larger than 4K -- up to 32K in size. That wasn't accounted for at the time, and such files are now showing up in the wild.\n\n```\n$ stat -c '%s %n' /usr/share/terminfo/x/xterm{,-256color}=20\n4156 /usr/share/terminfo/x/xterm\n4242 /usr/share/terminfo/x/xterm-256color\n```\n\nThe mentioned functions are the workers beneath unibi_from_term/env/file, so they're the most likely to be used by applications. However, they have a [hard-coded limit](https://github.com/neovim/unibilium/blob/31fef2218ea8a99686de7a4f1b22813591d1685f/uniutil.c#L46) of 4K, allocated on the stack.",
    "closed_at": null,
    "closed_by": null,
    "comment_data": [
        {
            "author_association": "MEMBER",
            "body": "Allocating 32K on the stack doesn't seem like a great idea.\n\nThe convenience functions could malloc the buffer, instead of using a stack allocation.\n\nOr the existing, [documented](https://github.com/neovim/unibilium/blob/31fef2218ea8a99686de7a4f1b22813591d1685f/doc/unibi_from_fd.pod?plain=1#L15), limitations of these functions could be left in place and add new APIs could be added (ones that accept a buffer from the caller, or explicitly malloc internally).",
            "created_at": "2026-06-13T20:03:10Z",
            "html_url": "https://github.com/neovim/unibilium/issues/32#issuecomment-4699636322",
